</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="716D7CB931AD02EDAA8DC5E32B46E01F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0F858A5E68DA314155F8EC5487FF176C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="47D27DC34E4D72F5706893B73743C38C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
From the Latin 
<emphasis id="33CB06F14C5BF4E86FC16501ED23EF30" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">ignitus</emphasis>
, set on fire, and 
<emphasis id="E119B5C85A0DF032A3E9EA905F7D4DA7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">macula</emphasis>
, spot or blot, in reference to the red and yellow spots of the forewing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="45C81C71A5F44AA90ECEF32CD22AF817" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="ACD6DACC8AB692641D0440EA92EFB453" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1DA0896AC1FAD6D236851906A410978B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Specimen MTD8238 shows a forewing pattern resembling that of 
<taxonomicName id="89C9B0F9C6BF003988C1F9E09858B913" genus="H." lsidName="H. ignitamaculae" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="ignitamaculae">
<emphasis id="5CD001CAE0D1DB4EBF6C052D0EB02465" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">H. ignitamaculae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., but with markings reduced. However, the thorn is absent in female genitalia.
</paragraph>
